## Services

For Phase 1, the backend should stay small: Auth, Stations, Sessions, Billing, Commands, and Health. Redis is optional at the start, but PostgreSQL should be the source of truth for users, stations, sessions, pricing rules, and audit events.

The station side should have exactly two processes:

- `station-shell`: login screen, QR/code entry, time-left UI, reconnect banner, local IPC client.
- `station-service`: local timer authority, launch/stop game executable, watchdog, offline queue, and signed event sync.


## DB schema

The minimum schema should model cafes, stations, users, session leases, price plans, and append-only station events. IтАЩd also add a tiny local SQLite DB inside `station-service` for offline lease state and unsynced events, because named-pipe IPC and service-style deployment make local durability cheap and reliable on Windows.[^3][^2]


| Table | Key fields | Notes |
| :-- | :-- | :-- |
| `cafes` | `id`, `name`, `timezone`, `currency`, `status` | One row per location. |
| `stations` | `id`, `cafe_id`, `code`, `name`, `device_fingerprint`, `status`, `last_seen_at`, `current_session_id` | `code` is used in QR/manual login. |
| `users` | `id`, `type`, `display_name`, `phone`, `wallet_balance`, `status` | `type`: walk_in, member, admin, staff. |
| `price_plans` | `id`, `cafe_id`, `name`, `billing_mode`, `rate_per_hour`, `min_minutes`, `active` | Keep billing_mode simple: hourly only in Phase 1. |
| `games` | `id`, `slug`, `name`, `launch_type`, `exe_path_template`, `active` | Only store a few curated games first. |
| `sessions` | `id`, `cafe_id`, `station_id`, `user_id`, `game_id`, `price_plan_id`, `status`, `started_at`, `ends_at`, `ended_at`, `billed_minutes`, `amount_due` | Core operational record. |
| `session_leases` | `id`, `session_id`, `station_id`, `lease_version`, `issued_at`, `expires_at`, `grace_seconds`, `signature` | Lets station continue safely when cloud drops. |
| `station_commands` | `id`, `station_id`, `session_id`, `type`, `payload_json`, `issued_by`, `issued_at`, `acked_at`, `status` | For start, extend, stop, ping, refresh-state. |
| `station_events` | `id`, `station_id`, `session_id`, `event_type`, `payload_json`, `created_at`, `source`, `seq_no` | Append-only audit stream from service. |
| `auth_tokens` | `id`, `user_id`, `kind`, `token_hash`, `expires_at`, `used_at` | QR/login tokens. |

Suggested enums:

```sql
station_status: OFFLINE | IDLE | RESERVED | IN_SESSION | LOCKED | ERROR
session_status: PENDING | ACTIVE | PAUSED | ENDED | EXPIRED | ABORTED
command_status: QUEUED | DELIVERED | ACKED | FAILED | EXPIRED
event_type: HEARTBEAT | SESSION_STARTED | SESSION_EXTENDED | SESSION_STOPPED |
            GAME_LAUNCHED | GAME_EXITED | TIMER_TICK | CONNECTIVITY_LOST |
            CONNECTIVITY_RESTORED | SHELL_CONNECTED | SHELL_DISCONNECTED
```


## IPC contracts

Named pipes are the cleanest Phase 1 IPC boundary on Windows for small control messages between the shell and service. Rust ecosystems already document Windows services and named-pipe IPC patterns well enough that this split is practical without inventing custom transport.[^2][^3]

Use one pipe, newline-delimited JSON, request-response by `correlationId`, and a shared secret or ACL so only your shell can connect.

```text
Pipe name:
\\.\pipe\gaming-cafe-station

Envelope:
{
  "v": 1,
  "type": "service.get_state",
  "correlationId": "01H...",
  "ts": "2026-04-19T17:05:00Z",
  "payload": {}
}
```

Core shell -> service messages:

```json
{ "v":1, "type":"service.ping", "correlationId":"...", "payload":{} }

{ "v":1, "type":"session.apply_lease", "correlationId":"...", "payload":{
  "sessionId":"sess_123",
  "stationId":"st_01",
  "leaseVersion":1,
  "startedAt":"2026-04-19T17:00:00Z",
  "endsAt":"2026-04-19T18:00:00Z",
  "graceSeconds":300,
  "signature":"base64..."
}}

{ "v":1, "type":"session.extend", "correlationId":"...", "payload":{
  "sessionId":"sess_123",
  "addMinutes":30,
  "leaseVersion":2,
  "signature":"base64..."
}}

{ "v":1, "type":"session.stop", "correlationId":"...", "payload":{
  "sessionId":"sess_123",
  "reason":"manager_stop",
  "signature":"base64..."
}}

{ "v":1, "type":"game.launch", "correlationId":"...", "payload":{
  "sessionId":"sess_123",
  "gameId":"valorant",
  "exePath":"C:\\Riot Games\\VALORANT\\live\\VALORANT.exe",
  "args":[]
}}

{ "v":1, "type":"game.terminate", "correlationId":"...", "payload":{
  "sessionId":"sess_123",
  "gameId":"valorant"
}}

{ "v":1, "type":"kiosk.set_mode", "correlationId":"...", "payload":{
  "enabled":true
}}
```

Core service -> shell messages:

```json
{ "v":1, "type":"ack", "correlationId":"...", "payload":{
  "ok":true
}}

{ "v":1, "type":"state.snapshot", "correlationId":"...", "payload":{
  "stationStatus":"IN_SESSION",
  "serviceStatus":"RUNNING",
  "activeSession":{
    "sessionId":"sess_123",
    "gameId":"valorant",
    "remainingSeconds":3290,
    "offlineMode":false
  },
  "activeGameProcess":{
    "pid":4242,
    "detected":true
  }
}}

{ "v":1, "type":"event.session_tick", "payload":{
  "sessionId":"sess_123",
  "remainingSeconds":3289
}}

{ "v":1, "type":"event.game_exited", "payload":{
  "sessionId":"sess_123",
  "gameId":"valorant",
  "exitCode":0
}}

{ "v":1, "type":"event.error", "payload":{
  "code":"GAME_NOT_FOUND",
  "message":"Configured executable missing"
}}
```

Validation rules:

- Service rejects stale `leaseVersion`.
- Service rejects unsigned mutating commands.
- Shell treats service time as authoritative for countdown.
- Backend treats `station_events.seq_no` as authoritative for reconciliation.


## First build order

Build these in sequence so Phase 1 stays shippable:

1. `api`: station registration, QR/code login, create session, extend session, stop session.
2. `station-service`: named pipe server, local SQLite, timer engine, heartbeat, one game launch adapter.
3. `station-shell`: Tauri login/time-left UI, WebSocket client, IPC client, reconnect states. TauriтАЩs maintained WebSocket support is enough for this client role without embedding your own socket stack in the UI layer.[^1]
4. `manager-web`: station list, active session card, extend/stop controls, manual station refresh.

The first end-to-end happy path should be: create session -> issue lease -> shell sends `session.apply_lease` -> service persists lease -> service launches game -> service emits ticks/events -> manager can extend or stop the session. The Windows service piece is worth doing early because Rust already has a dedicated crate for service-style processes, and that decision affects install/update/permissions from day one.[^2]

